  <h1>Types of Rideshare Accident Claims</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Passenger claims (Period 2/3)</h2><p>Strongest position. $1M Uber/Lyft coverage available. Passenger has no comparative fault issue. Claims go against the rideshare company&rsquo;s insurer (James River Insurance for Uber; various carriers for Lyft depending on state).</p>
  <h2>Third-party claims (Periods 1–3)</h2><p>Pedestrian, cyclist, or occupant of another vehicle struck by the rideshare driver. Coverage depends on phase. Period 2/3: $1M. Period 1: $50K/$100K contingent. Period 0: driver&rsquo;s personal insurance only.</p>
  <h2>Driver UIM claims (Period 2/3)</h2><p>If the rideshare driver is injured by an uninsured/underinsured motorist during a trip, Uber and Lyft provide UIM coverage of up to $1M. Driver must have comprehensive/collision to trigger contingent coverage for vehicle damage.</p>
  <h2>Independent contractor disputes</h2><p>Some plaintiffs argue for direct negligence liability against Uber/Lyft (negligent hiring, negligent entrustment, negligent failure to address known dangerous drivers). These claims are harder to win but can produce significant recovery when Uber/Lyft had notice of a driver&rsquo;s dangerous history.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-rideshare-accident-claims-work">how claims work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
